In PHP, you can combine arrays using the `` array_merge_recursive() `` function from the `` RecursiveArrayIterator `` class. Here's an example of how to use it:


```php
// Define two arrays
$array1 = [
    'key1' => 'value1',
    'key2' => 'value2',
];

$array2 = [
    'key3' => 'value3',
    'key4' => 'value4',
];

// Create an iterator for each array
$iterator1 = new RecursiveArrayIterator($array1);
$iterator2 = new RecursiveArrayIterator($array2);

// Use the iterator to traverse the arrays
while (true) {
    // Check if the current key exists in both arrays
    if (isset($iterator1->current()) && isset($iterator2->current())) {
        // If it does, update the value in the second array using the current value from the first array
        $iterator2->current()['key'] = $iterator1->current()['key'];
    }
    // Move to the next key or break out of the loop
    $iterator1->next();
    if (!$iterator1->valid()) {
        break;
    }
}

print_r($array1);  // Output: ['key1' => 'value1', 'key2' => 'value2']
print_r($array2);  // Output: ['key3' => 'value3', 'key4' => 'value4']

```

