Yes, you can use Perl to convert all .mp4 files in the current directory to .mkv files using the `ffmpeg` command line tool. Here is a Perl script that does this:
```
#!/usr/bin/env perl

use strict;
use warnings;

use FindBin;
use File::Path qw(make_path);

use FFMpeg;
use FFMpeg::CommandLine;

# Make the current directory the search path for files
chdir($FindBin::Bin);

# Get a list of all .mp4 files in the current directory
my $mp4_files = FFMpeg::CommandLine->new->search('*.mp4');

# Convert each .mp4 file to .mkv
foreach my $file (@$mp4_files) {
  FFMpeg::CommandLine->new->set_input($file)
    ->set_output($file)
    ->add_option('-c', 'copy')
    ->add_option('-f', 'mpeg4')
    ->add_option('-codec', 'copy')
    ->add_option('-tag', 'mkv')
    ->run();
}
```
This script uses the `FFMpeg` module to interact with the `ffmpeg` command line tool. It first uses `FFMpeg::CommandLine->new` to create a new instance of the `FFMpeg` module, and then uses `->search('*.mp4')` to get a list of all .mp4 files in the current directory. It then loops over each file in the list, and runs the `FFMpeg::CommandLine->new->set_input($file)` to set the input file, and then runs `->set_output($file) ->add_option('-c', 'copy') ->add_option('-f', 'mpeg4') ->add_option('-codec', 'copy') ->add_option('-tag', 'mkv')` to set the output file and specify that the video and audio streams should be copied from the input file to the output file without re-encoding.

