Yes, it is possible to convert videos using Perl. Here is a Perl script that converts all .mp4 files in the current directory to .mkv using ffmpeg:
```
#!/usr/bin/env perl

use strict;
use warnings;

use File::Find;
use File::Path qw(make_path);
use Getopt::Std;

use constant {
    MKV => '/usr/bin/ffmpeg',
    OPTIONS => '+c:v libx264 -crf 18 -c:a libmp3lame -b:a 192k'
};

my %opts;
getopts('', \%opts);

if (@ARGV != 1) {
    print STDERR "Usage: $0 <input_dir>\n";
    exit 1;
}

my $input_dir = $ARGV[0];
my $output_dir = $input_dir . '/output';
make_path($output_dir) unless -d $output_dir;

find({ no_path => 1 }, $input_dir) => {
    my $file = $_[0];
    next if $file !~ /.mp4$/;

    $file = $output_dir . '/' . $file;
    $file =~ s/\.mp4$/.mkv$/;

    system(MKV, *$opts{OPTIONS}, $file);
};
```
This script uses the `File::Find` module to iterate over all files in the specified input directory. For each file, it runs the `ffmpeg` command to convert the file to a .mkv file.

The script uses the `getopts` function to parse command-line options. The `-c:v libx264` and `-c:a libmp3lame` options specify the video and audio codecs to use, respectively. The `-crf 18` and `-b:a 192k` options specify the video and audio bitrates, respectively. These options are stored in the `%opts` hash and passed to the `ffmpeg` command using the `system` function.

